<p>Computing:</p> <blockquote> <p>Once the device is reset, it starts the process of pairing itself with the owner‚Äôs Wi-Fi network. Because the exchange of information between the device and the app is performed via an unsecured HTTP connection, it enables a hacker within range of the Wi-Fi network to intercept the login details.</p> <p>The patch released by Ring to mitigate the vulnerability ensures that the device uses an HTTPS connection while broadcasting a Wi-Fi signal for the phone to grab. The connection is also secured through a digital certificate, signed by the firm and validated by the app.</p> </blockquote> <p>Ring was using HTTP? That seems less like a mistake and more like gross incompetence.</p> <div> <a title="Permanent link to ‚ÄòAmazon Patches Ring Video Doorbell Vulnerability That Could Allow Hackers to Breach Owner‚Äôs Wi-Fi Network ‚Äô" href="https://daringfireball.net/linked/2019/11/08/amazon-ring-http">&nbsp;‚òÖ&nbsp;</a> </div>
