<summary type="text">
It was a simple four-tap process to sign up‚Äâ‚Äî‚Äâfast, easy, and obvious.
</summary>
<content type="html" xml:base="https://daringfireball.net/" xml:lang="en">
<![CDATA[
<p>I‚Äôve been curious ever since the ‚Äúfirst year free with the purchase of a new Apple device‚Äù deal was announced how exactly it was going to work. For me, it was seamless. I went to the TV app on my iPhone (which is, <a href="https://daringfireball.net/linked/2019/10/31/ios-13-2-background-app-massacre">unfortunately</a>, running iOS 13.2‚Äâ‚Äî‚Äânot sure if that matters), and when I tapped on ‚ÄúThe Morning Show‚Äù, it recognized that I had purchased a new iPhone and qualified for the year-long free subscription.</p> <p>It was a simple four-tap process to sign up‚Äâ‚Äî‚Äâfast, easy, and obvious. Here‚Äôs a little diagram I made illustrating the four steps.</p> <p><a href="/misc/2019/11/apple-tv-plus-signup.png" class="noborder"> <img src = "/misc/2019/11/apple-tv-plus-signup.png" alt = "A series of 4 screenshots illustrating the Apple TV+ signup process." width = 425 /></a></p> <p>The fourth step is so super obvious that, rather than direct your attention to the button where you agree to the Apple Pay confirmation, I pointed instead to a layout bug that has plagued me for at least three or four years with this Apple Pay confirmation sheet. To wit, my iTunes Apple ID email address gets mis-wrapped as ‚Äú<em>myaddress</em>@daringfireball.ne‚Äù + ‚Äút‚Äù. This annoys me, tremendously, every time I see it. It‚Äôs as though every single time I confirm an Apple Pay purchase with my phone, Apple throws a little bit of sand into my eyes. It‚Äôd be bad enough if the email address were broken between the ‚Äúdaringfireball‚Äù and the ‚Äú.net‚Äù. A long enough email address has to break somewhere. But to just break at the ‚Äút‚Äù‚Äâ‚Äî‚Äâa one-character widow that doesn‚Äôt even vaguely fall at a natural break‚Äâ‚Äî‚Äâis a violation of every known <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050310054738/http://www.melbpc.org.au/pcupdate/9100/9112article4.htm">typographic norm for splitting words</a> that don‚Äôt fit. And just look at it‚Äâ‚Äî‚Äâclearly there‚Äôs enough room for the ‚Äút‚Äù there. It <em>should</em> fit, which makes it all the more maddening.</p> <p>The other cool thing about Apple TV+ is that you can watch it using the <a href="https://tv.apple.com/">tv.apple.com</a> domain from any device with a supported browser. I wasn‚Äôt expecting that, but should have, given that <a href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/9/5/20851576/apple-music-web-player-interface-beta-browser-streaming">Apple Music became web-enabled</a> a few weeks ago. Nice work.</p>
