<updated>2019-10-31T22:27:37Z</updated>
<author>
<name>John Gruber</name>
<uri>http://daringfireball.net/</uri>
</author>
<content type="html" xml:base="https://daringfireball.net/linked/" xml:lang="en">
<![CDATA[
<p>Jack Dorsey, in a tweet thread:</p> <blockquote> <p>For instance, it‚Äòs not credible for us to say: ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre working hard to stop people from gaming our systems to spread misleading info, buuut if someone pays us to target and force people to see their political ad‚Ä¶ well‚Ä¶ they can say whatever they want!‚Äù [‚Ä¶]</p> <p>This isn‚Äôt about free expression. This is about paying for reach. And paying to increase the reach of political speech has significant ramifications that today‚Äôs democratic infrastructure may not be prepared to handle. It‚Äôs worth stepping back in order to address.</p> </blockquote> <p>Political advertising is a drop in the bucket of Twitter‚Äôs overall revenue, but that‚Äôs true of Facebook too. ‚Äú<em>The money matters to us</em>‚Äù would be a terrible justification for Facebook‚Äôs policy of allowing political ads to spread falsehoods, but the money <em>doesn‚Äôt</em> even matter to them. Facebook is allowing political ads to spread falsehoods because Facebook wants political ads to spread falsehoods. There‚Äôs no other explanation.</p> <div> <a title="Permanent link to ‚ÄòTwitter to Stop Accepting Political Ads Globally‚Äô" href="https://daringfireball.net/linked/2019/10/31/twitter-political-ads">&nbsp;‚òÖ&nbsp;</a> </div>
