<updated>2019-10-29T02:50:48Z</updated>
<author>
<name>John Gruber</name>
<uri>http://daringfireball.net/</uri>
</author>
<content type="html" xml:base="https://daringfireball.net/linked/" xml:lang="en">
<![CDATA[
<p>From a letter signed by 250 employees, obtained by The New York Times:</p> <blockquote> <p>We‚Äôre reaching out to you, the leaders of this company, because we‚Äôre worried we‚Äôre on track to undo the great strides our product teams have made in integrity over the last two years. We work here because we care, because we know that even our smallest choices impact communities at an astounding scale. We want to raise our concerns before it‚Äôs too late.</p> <p>Free speech and paid speech are not the same thing.</p> </blockquote> <p>Many are noting, correctly, that Facebook has 35,000 employees (which sounds like too many to me), so 250 signatures is a small percentage. But if this accurately reflects a large number of employees‚Äô thoughts, it could be trouble for Facebook.</p> <p><strong>See also:</strong> <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/28/technology/facebook-mark-zuckerberg-political-ads.html?module=inline">Mike Isaac‚Äôs report for the NYT on the letter</a>.</p> <div> <a title="Permanent link to ‚ÄòRead the Letter Facebook Employees Sent to Mark Zuckerberg About Political Ads‚Äô" href="https://daringfireball.net/linked/2019/10/28/facebook-employee-letter">&nbsp;‚òÖ&nbsp;</a> </div>
