<title>Apple‚Äôs AirPods Pro Web Page: Scrolljacking Hell</title>
<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://www.apple.com/airpods-pro/"/>
<link rel="shorturl" type="text/html" href="http://df4.us/rxh"/>
<link rel="related" type="text/html" href="https://daringfireball.net/linked/2019/10/28/airpods-pro-scrolljacking-hell"/>
<id>tag:daringfireball.net,2019:/linked//6.36197</id>
<published>2019-10-28T20:07:50Z</published>
<updated>2019-10-28T21:57:20Z</updated>
<author>
<name>John Gruber</name>
<uri>http://daringfireball.net/</uri>
</author>
<content type="html" xml:base="https://daringfireball.net/linked/" xml:lang="en">
<![CDATA[
<p>The AirPods Pro ‚Äúoverview‚Äù web page is a strange beast. It pegs my 2015 MacBook Pro‚Äôs CPU‚Äâ‚Äî‚Äâ<em>even when I‚Äôm not scrolling</em>. I closed the tab a few minutes ago and my fan is still running. The animation is very jerky and scrolling feels so slow. There‚Äôs so much <a href="https://www.discoverydesign.co.uk/blog/post/scroll-hijacking-why-scrolljacking-is-a-usability-nightmare/">scrolljacking</a> that you have to scroll or page down several times just to go to the next section of the page. The animation is at least smooth on my iPad and iPhone, but even there, it feels like a thousand swipes to get to the bottom of the page. It‚Äôs a design that makes it feel like they don‚Äôt want you to keep reading. </p> <p>Disable JavaScript (easily toggled if you enable <a href="https://support.apple.com/guide/safari/use-the-developer-tools-in-the-develop-menu-sfri20948/mac">Safari‚Äôs Develop menu</a>) and the page is easy to read and looks great. I can‚Äôt recall an example where scrolljacking makes a website so much worse.</p> <p><strong>Update:</strong> Nick Heer (of <a href="https://pxlnv.com/">Pixel Envy</a> fame) messaged me to point out that the <a href="https://www.apple.com/ipad-pro/">iPad Pro product page</a> gives the AirPods Pro page a run for its money for top spot in the Scrolljacking Hall of Shame. The iPad Pro page doesn‚Äôt peg my MacBook Pro‚Äôs CPU, but it scrolls the view <em>horizontally</em> while you scroll vertically.</p> <div> <a title="Permanent link to ‚ÄòApple‚Äôs AirPods Pro Web Page: Scrolljacking Hell‚Äô" href="https://daringfireball.net/linked/2019/10/28/airpods-pro-scrolljacking-hell">&nbsp;‚òÖ&nbsp;</a> </div>
]]>
